http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Long before Bandon became AT&T’s outpost in rural Oregon, it was a critical node in an undersea cable network: the U.S. military’s Sound Surveillance System (SOSUS). From the Pacific coast, SOSUS connected hydrophones and picked up sonic traces of subaquatic movements, from the deployment of Soviet submarines to migrations of whales. Officers stationed at Naval Facility Coos Head tuned into these underwater listening posts and collected data on enemy operations. The Coos Head facility, first opened in 1958, was closed twenty-nine years later in 1987. Improvements in signal-processing had replaced manpower with computers, and as the Cold War wound down the number of Naval Facilities was reduced. Given AT&T’s tight ties with the U.S. Navy, and their assistance in developing SOSUS, it was unsurprising when nine years later, they chose Bandon as a landing point for their newest transpacific cable system, TPC-5.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: This tag specifies that the associated page is a cable.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Across history, there have been three kinds of cable technology: copper telegraph cables, coaxial telephone cables, and fiber-optic internet cables. To create a page for a new cable, see the reference page for cables.

Completed in 2000, the consortium-owned China-U.S. Cable Network was the first direct cable route between the two countries. It consists of dual Pacific crossings, forming a ring structure with connections along the west coast of the U.S. and between several Southeast Asian hubs. Only a year after it entered service, however, the anchor of a fishing boat off Chongming Island disrupted much of the traffic between China and the U.S..
The Japanese Government linked Nagasaki with Taiwan in 1910.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: On AtlanticCable.com, many landings indicated by "Mogi, Nagasaki-ken, Japan"

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Like many port cities in Asia, Nagasaki was “discovered” by imperial powers – in this case, the Portuguese – and developed for trade. In the nineteenth century, Nagasaki became a busy transit point, with a vibrant ship-building industry, an anchorage site for the Japanese navy, and a telegraph cable landing point. Three years after its first submarine telegraph cable was landed in 1871, the telegraph company established a headquarters here, in a large two-story office building abutting the harbor. Within a few years, Japan would build up its internal landlines, and the country would be connected to the rest of the world via Nagasaki. The importance of this station was clear to Japan and its enemies. Described as “clutching the aeortic artery of international communications in Japan,” Nagasaki, as a hub and military harbor, was also a target. The cable to Vladivostok was taken out of service during the Russo-Japanese War, but the city remained undamaged. During World War II, however, Nagasaki was hit with the atomic bomb, the second and last to ever be deployed, killing several hundred thousand people. After the Japanese surrender, the city would slowly rebuild. Old communications lines were taken out of service, and new coaxial cables laid in their place.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: You make your way through sludge and silt to come ashore – quite a different experience from the clear seawater of the southern Japanese islands. A Spanish and then Dutch colony in the seventeenth century, Tanshui (also known as Dansheui) grew to become the largest port in Taiwan by the late 1800s. Coal and tea were exported in vast quantities from the natural harbor where the Tanshui (or Tamsui) River meets the Strait of Taiwan. In 1887, an underwater telegraph cable joined the bustling city to Fuzhou on the Chinese mainland, and a year later the Taipei Telegraph Academy opened nearby. But in the early twentieth century, the buildup of silt at the river mouth caused much of the shipping traffic to move east to Keelung. While its port status dwindled, Tanshui retained its position as an international cable hub. Several fiber-optic systems arrived in the early 2000s, linking the town to points throughout East Asia and the Pacific. Twin landing stations, owned by competing telecom carriers, are situated along a quiet beach west of the city, famous for vivid sunsets and a popular leisure destination for residents of Taipei.
In 1905, following the Russo-Japanese war, the Japanese laid a line from the northern tip of Japan to Sakhalin Island.

The island is an unwelcoming place, yet a center of conflict. Anton Chekov describes it quite simply as “hell.” Peopled mostly by soldiers and life-long prisoners, with a few fishermen, Alexandrovsk-Sakhalinsky is damp, cold, and icy in the winter months. A small harbor town on the island of Sakhalin, off the edge of the Russian mainland and north of the northernmost part of Japan, it became the location of a Russian military post in 1881, established to oversee the prison camps and nearby exile settlements. Political dissidents, criminals, and ethnic minorities were sent to live here in large communal cells and to work the land for the rest of their lives. Chekov lived here in 1890 while working on a treatise about the Tsarist penal system. Arriving before the completion of the Trans-Siberian railroad or the trans-Pacific cable, he traveled the 6,000 miles across Siberia by coach, and then across the water by boat to the island. He wrote of his arrival: "Along the shore near the pier some 50 convicts were wandering, obviously idle; some wore overalls, others in jackets or grey cloth coats. When I approached, they removed their caps.  It is possible that no writer has ever previously received such an honour." Fifteen years later, during the Russo-Japanese war, the southern half of the island would be taken by the Japanese and united with the island of Hokkaido by a submarine communications cable.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Today, Wakkanai is the northernmost city in Japan, with one of the island’s colder climates and record snowfalls totaling over 250 inches in a year. Yet a century ago the Japanese empire stretched even further north to the 50th parallel on the island of Sakhalin, taken from the Russians during the Russo-Japanese war. Wakkanai was a strategic outpost connecting the two islands and a submarine cable was laid to carry communications between their shores. After the Russians took back Sakhalin during World War II, forcing refugees south into Wakkanai, the city remained a strategic site. The United States’ Wakkanai Air Station, established shortly after the war, used radar installations to gather intelligence during the Cold War. Only miles from Sakhalin, and not far from the border between Russia and China, the listening post amassed information about critical events in the region for decades, pre-figuring the covert collection of data today by the National Security Agency and others.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: According to local legend, Pohnpei was created when ancient sailors piled rocks in the middle of the ocean. To protect the new island from waves, they surrounded it with a ring of coral reef. You cross this threshold on your approach to Kolonia, Pohnpei’s main port and largest town. This is a place of sharp contrasts. With no natural sand beaches to ease your transition, you surface abruptly near the city center where the Federated States of Micronesia Telecommunications Company cable station is located. The modern, two-story building and large satellite dish stand next to the stalls of street-vendors selling yams, bananas, breadfruit, and coconuts. On the blocks around the station, newer houses and hotels are interspersed with relics from the colonial era, including a Spanish fort from the 1880s, a turn-of-the-century German Catholic church, and several rusted, vine-covered Japanese tanks left over from World War II. Beyond that, paved roads quickly give way to mountainous jungle.

Named after its owner, Hannon Armstrong, and operator Truestone, this system initially linked Guam to the Ronald Regan Ballistic Missile Defense Test Site in the Marshall Islands and was funded by the U.S. Army. In 2010, extensions were made to Majuro and the Federated States of Micronesia, greatly increasing speeds over existing satellite transmissions.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: For decades, Taiwan’s cables had been concentrated at its northern and southern tips. While the Tanshui and Toucheng stations are on the fringes of Taipei, the Chunghwa Telecom station is located in the rural southern township of Fangshan. Most traffic to Southeast Asia, whether from Taiwan, East Asia, or North America, passes through the Bashi Strait, the narrow passage separating Taiwan and the Philippines. Fangshan was the ideal gateway to this route until recently, when a spate of natural disasters severed numerous cable links. An earthquake in September 1999 broke Taiwan’s terrestrial backbone, one undersea cable, and caused cell sites and radio relays to collapse. The 2006 Hengchun earthquake caused submarine landslides that took out nine undersea links. Most recently,  Typhoon Morakot disrupted six international cables and 1700 wireless base stations, in addition to taking 500 lives. Fangshan, perched on the edge of the Bashi Strait, is no longer a popular interconnection point for undersea traffic.

Stretching a total of 24,000 miles between 39 landing sites, Southeast Asia-Middle East-Western Europe 3 (SeaMeWe-3) is more than twice as long as its intercontinental predecessor, SeaMeWe-2. The optical cable system was commissioned in 2000 by an international consortium of nearly 100 corporate investors.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: When it was finished in December 2005, the consortium-owned Southeast Asia-Middle East-Western Europe 4 cable provided both additional bandwidth and greater redundancy along the bulk of the previous-generation SeaMeWe-3 line between the Mediterranean and Singapore. SeaMeWe-3, however, extends significantly further to points in China, Japan, Australia, the U.K., and Germany, among others.

To get to California’s oldest still operational cable landing point, established in Point Arena in 1957, you would have to travel over a hundred miles north from San Francisco on narrow wooded roads. The cable station is positioned on a bluff overlooking the Pacific. Across the road from the station, families picnic at a campsite. Cows graze in a nearby pasture. Between the station and the beach, a sign restricts access to a “sensitive habitat area.” At first glance these environments, and the signs indicating environmental preservation, appear to secure both wildlife and cables, protecting infrastructure from perception and potential tampering. But such environments also pose a problem to those laying undersea cables. At this station, cable builders had to undergo extra permitting,  and ultimately delay, to ensure that they did not endanger the Point Arena mountain beaver.

Trans-Pacific Cable 4 was put in the water in 1991, only a few years after TPC-3 was laid, yet it doubled the capacity of the earlier system. As the first fiber cable that linked directly from the USA to Japan, it was also the last system to be landed on Canada's west coast. After it was withdrawn from service in 2003, the Port Alberni station ceased to operate transoceanic systems.

For roughly two decades beginning in the late 1970s, this small village in the northwest Philippines was linked to the urban centers of Singapore, Hong Kong, and Okinawa. By 1980, Currimao was considered one of the largest and most advanced cable hubs in the world. But when the Asia-America Gateway system was being built in the early 2000s, the Philippine Long Distance Telephone Company selected a landing site more than a hundred miles south in the province of La Union, closer to Metro Manila. As quickly as it appeared, Currimao faded from the network map. Today it is perhaps best known for a series of coral rock formations, shaped by the ocean into dramatic caverns and spires over thousands of years.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Waves crash up against a thick seawall that spans the coast of Toucheng. Much of the shore here in northeast Taiwan is comprised of sand rock, eroded by ocean waves and monsoon winds. Spectacular surface formations are cut into the sedimentary rock, some locals observe that these even resemble tofu. Yet the erosion here is not entirely natural. The presence of manmade structures on 56% of Taiwan’s coast, this seawall included, has sped up the disappearance of the coast. These structures interrupt the flow of sand, causing it to accumulate on one side and to quickly erode on the other. The nearby Toucheng beach, which once stretched for two kilometers, is now severely diminished, and the coast has retreated up to 100 meters inland. This seawall keeps the shoreline intact for both waves and cable stations, but provides an additional challenge for cable laying. Companies have to bore a hole through the thick walls in order to thread their networks through.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Sri Racha is an industrial economic center in the province of Chonburi, about an hour’s drive from Bangkok on an eight-lane freeway. Rice, sugar, rubber, tapioca, coconut, and seafood are all produced in vast quantities before being exported from Laem Chabang, the largest container port in Thailand and one of the busiest commercial harbors in the world. Shipping lines dovetail with the paths of underwater cables that link Sri Racha to other communication hubs in Southeast Asia and across the Pacific. Most of the district’s beaches are muddy and rocky, with development often reaching the water’s edge. But cables land on one of the few slivers of sand in the area north of Laem Chabang before making their way inland past factories and manufacturing plants to the state-owned cable station.

Asia-America Gateway (AAG), opened in 2009, was the first high-bandwidth optical cable to provide a direct link between Southeast Asia and California (via the Philippines, Guam, and Hawaii). Positioned further south than other trans-Pacific routes, AAG avoids the seismically active areas near Taiwan where earthquakes are known to cause cable disruptions.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/rightsHolder.value: Hannon Armstrong,  Federated States of Micronesia Telecommunications Company,  Marshall Islands Telecommunications Authority

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Overcoming powerful waves and currents, you reach the coral rubble shores of Majuro. Signals travel to this ring-shaped atoll through a commercial extension of a U.S. military cable, completed in 2010, that links Guam’s network hub to a missile defense facility on Kwajalein. Though geographically isolated, Majuro is the capital city and commercial center of the Marshall Islands, home to nearly half the country’s population. From the beach, you move underneath crowded streets to the cable station, owned by the National Telecommunications Authority, next to a sports field and two large satellite dishes. Go a few blocks further, and you reach the Majuro lagoon, which holds a busy regional port. Ships arrive delivering supplies to the resource-starved island and depart carrying exports including aquarium fish and black pearls. More recently, the low-lying city has emerged as a node in the struggle to mitigate rising sea levels. In 2013, leaders of sixteen Pacific nations gathered to sign the Majuro Declaration to take action on global climate change.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: At a March 17, 2009 launch for Globe Telecom’s cable station in Ballesteros, President Arroyo held the ends of two oversized blue cables as representatives from Globe and India’s Tata Communications brought them together. Located more than 250 miles north of the hotel ballroom in Metro Manila where the ceremony took place, the Ballesteros station provides redundancy for existing cable infrastructure in southern Luzon, some of which was disrupted by the 2006 earthquake off the coast of Taiwan. It joins Tata’s Asian and Pacific networks to a system of terrestrial lines that weave south, roughly following the path of the country’s longest river, used for centuries to transport crops that grow along its shores. The small tobacco-producing community of Ballesteros is a few miles west of the river mouth, a safe distance from the flooding that occurs during monsoon season.
This cable extends Tata Communications’ global network into Southeast Asia, connecting major hubs in Singapore and Hong Kong with smaller stations in Vietnam and the Philippines.

The Tanguisson Beach station, built to house American networks during the Cold War era, resembles an underground bunker. Entering, you descend several stories down a fortified stairwell and even then, can only access the equipment room once admitted through a secure metal door. Immediately inside the entrance is a decontamination chamber, a former precaution for nuclear attack, and now a storage closet. Everything inside is redundant in case the domestic infrastructure fails. Multiple, completely separated generators comprise backups for building power and air-conditioning units. Independent battery plants sustain the equipment. During the coaxial era, Tanguisson was staffed by at least two employees at all times, but was often occupied by many more. On the wall, you witness evidence of the community formed here: yearbook-style photos of all of the AT&T stations in the Pacific: Makaha, Keawa‘ula, Bandon, San Luis Obispo, and Manchester. Each has an image of the station, and photos of the people who worked there, with their name and position listed underneath, grouped as a school class would be. Photographs of the cable ships, AT&T cable landings, and maps of Guam decorate the walls. Due to the massive downsizings that have occurred since the 1980s, far fewer people work at Tanguisson today. The cable community, however, still exists.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The small town of Nasugbu, strategically located on the South China Sea only sixty miles from Metro Manila, is the largest network hub in the Philippines. In the 1990s, the Philippine Long Distance Telephone Company opened the country’s first international cable station, which towers over the palm trees and bamboo structures that line the beach. Just down the street is Globe Telecom’s newer facility, an anchor point for the Southeast Asia Japan cable system. Large walls surround both stations and the place where cables enter the water is unmarked. On their journey out to sea, they pass the remains of a Spanish galleon, sunk by the Dutch navy in 1600. Discovered in 1992, the shipwreck became one of the most important finds in underwater archeology. A replica, along with a museum and resort, were built on nearby Fortune Island but have since fallen into disrepair.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/rightsHolder.value: Tata Communications

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The cable lands on Back Beach, a strip of towering upscale hotels, small seafood restaurants, and military installations left over from the American War. It winds under an enormous temporary infrastructure of beach chairs and food carts that support weekenders from Saigon, past the bunker-like buildings that fortress the beach, and inland to the VTI cable station in the center of Vung Tau, identifiable by its huge radio tower. Behind the cable station, a statue of a woman holding a cell phone brings the site good luck. For many years, indeed, Vung Tau has been lucky: since the United States military landed their first undersea telephone on Back Beach, all of the subsequent cables have chosen this spot, from the TVH cable in 1993 to the TGN Intra-Asia cable in 2009. Yet the latest link, the Asia-America Gateway cable, has not been so fortunate. Since its initiation it has been cut several times, severely affecting internet traffic in Vietnam.

A 12th-century sea wall lines the edge of a small village where cables land. Locals come here to take in the panorama, looking east across the ocean. The clear seawater carries you up to white, rocky beaches, abutted by deep green brush leading into steep hills and low forests. The history of this village stretches back hundreds of years, when the sea wall and castle were built, forming the administrative and cultural center of the area. Yet the remoteness of the village made it appealing to cable companies during the coaxial period. After the destruction of World War II, companies surfaced cables far away from urban centers, like Okinawa City, which might be potential targets. In the 1970s and 1980s, a number of important international cables were landed here in Gushikami, making this rural land a submarine communications hub. More recently, the abandoned TPC-2 cable to Guam was revived for geophysical observations rather than telephone calls.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Ninomiya was the first landing site for trans-Pacific coaxial cables in Japan, built in 1964 to receive TPC-1 from Guam. Unlike many modern stations, it is located in a central residential area populated by commuters to Odawara and Tokyo-Yokohama. Even though Ninomiya is linked to these urban areas, the greenery of Azumayama Park makes them easy to leave behind. Climb up the hill behind the station and you will enter the park, passing several shrines and temples on your journey to the summit. Dense woods open onto a grassy plain with commanding views of Sagami Bay and Mount Fuji. Artist Hokusai Katsushika included this vista in his series of woodblock prints of Fuji as seen from different Japanese towns, drawing Ninomiya into an early-nineteenth-century visual network.

Famous for its fortifications more than its receptiveness, Taku has been a critical gateway to China since the 1500s. It is just downriver from the busy trading city of Tianjin, where the Hai connects to the Yellow and Yangtze rivers, and boats filled with goods have traveled for centuries. The water that connects Taku also made it vulnerable. To protect against Japanese pirates, the Chinese erected forts here in the 16th century. During the Opium Wars of the 19th century, these forts were expanded in response to concerns about Western imperial invasion. The concerns were valid: in 1858 the British won a battle here which opened the port to foreigners, allowing foreign legations, Christian missionaries, and the legal import of opium. The site remained highly contested for the rest of the century. In 1900, the Chinese government commissioned both the Great Northern Telegraph Company and the Eastern Extension Telegraph Company to lay cables to Taku. Things were tense: signals were often intercepted, foreign boats lurked in the harbor, Chinese troops filled the forts, and almost 2400 Russian soldiers were stationed in Tianjin. In June of that year, as the Boxer Rebellion erupted in Beijing, the occupying western nations collaboratively and successfully attacked the Taku Forts in a violent battle, leaving the area awash in “rivers of blood.” As was the case in many locales, cables followed conflict, and a month later, a German company began the construction on its own telegraph to Taku.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Tschifu is today called Yantai, meaning “smoky tower.” In a way, this harbor town was always a critical communications node: the name refers back to the Ming Dynasty, when locals would light smoky fires to warn the village of approaching Japanese pirates. On the north-eastern tip of the Shandong Peninsula, Tschifu was directly south of Dairen, due west of Seoul, and straight north from Shanghai. Its central location made it an ideal cable hub during the telegraph era. In the first decade of the twentieth century, ten cables were landed here, connecting to Tsingtau, Port Arthur, Taku, Dairen, Shanghai, and Wei-hai-wei. Even before the cables were landed, the city had long been an important traffic hub: it had been an international trading port for almost half a century and seventeen nations had established embassies there.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Shima is a major hub with connections to six active international cable networks, but it remains largely invisible to local residents. While cables are hidden, several festivals call attention to the surrounding ocean, known for its abundant marine life since at least the eighth century. Every June, a twenty-foot wooden spiny lobster is paraded through the city streets to encourage a bountiful harvest season. And in September, four men carry an oversized waraji (traditional straw sandal) into the ocean, setting it adrift. This ritual is designed to ward off Dandarabocchi, a mythological giant so large that his footsteps create lakes. Afterwards, spectators gather on the beach for dancing and a fireworks display.

The Australia-Japan Cable (AJC) links the two countries via Guam. When it was completed in 2001, it became “Australia’s largest connection yet to the global information highways,” according to an industry newsletter. The cable reaches depths of over 9,000 meters and forms a “collapsed ring” structure with twin lines spanning each leg of the system. A private company owned by Japanese and Australian telecoms was set up to design, build, and operate the cable until its projected retirement in 2026.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Đà Nẵng is a city divided by a river. Before the first bridge was built in 2000, residents had to take a ferry between the eastern shore, the site of the former French colonial settlement, and the western peninsula, which shelters the city from the sea. On the western shore lived poor fishermen, who have since moved away as beach resorts have populated the coast, extending south several kilometers to the site of Đà Nẵng’s international cable station. Like Vung Tau to the south, Đà Nẵng had long been interconnected into expansive undersea networks, first as part of the French colonial cable system and later as part of the Americans' wartime communications strategy. Đà Nẵng’s international cable station, however, was the first built with the support of the national telecommunications carrier, Vietnam Posts and Telecommunications. While the city's infrastructures, from bridges to cable systems, bring connections, they also bring an expansion of capitalism, providing benefits to some at the expense of others.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: As a landing site for the 1983 ASEAN cable, Songkhla was the first station in Thailand to receive underwater telephone links. Cables surface on the idyllic Ban Kao Seng beach near the country’s largest natural lake, the same place where invading Japanese troops landed at the start of the Second World War. Years earlier, according to local folklore, a wealthy governor from the south of Thailand was sailing up the coast with a fortune in gold when his ship ran aground near Ban Kao Seng. Stranded, the governor ordered his fortune buried, committed suicide, and left instructions for his severed head to be placed on the rocky cliffs above the beach. The name Kao Seng derives from the treasure’s supposed value: 900,000 baht. Some believe it’s still buried there alongside several underwater cables entering the Gulf of Thailand.

Constructed through an early-2000s partnership between Singapore’s SingTel, the Communications Authority of Thailand, and Telkom Indonesia, this cable links the three countries across the South China Sea.

Heading inland to the Makaha cable station, you surface in a parking lot, in a manhole barely visible under the dirt. Along the beaches to the south of this town reside hundreds of houseless people. O‘ahu’s west shore is home to one of the state’s largest native communities and largest homeless population. In Makaha alone, 32% of its residents live in poverty. Yet, the west shore is also a transit point for a large percentage of the state’s international signal traffic. Since the 1960s, almost all of the island’s coaxial and fiber-optic cables have terminated at three cable stations along this short 30-kilometer stretch. The seemingly divergent histories of telecommunications success and economic deprivation in the area are intertwined, linked to the area's long-standing military occupation. Weapons testing sites and military installations, such as the Lualualei Naval Reservation and the Schofield Barracks, displaced residents from the west shore’s inland valleys. At the same time, the U.S. military was once one of the biggest customers of the cable networks, giving them both an economic boost and a layer of protection when they were set up during the Cold War.

Fiber optic systems, which encode signals in light and send them down a thread of glass, have been in development since the early 1980s. Given the conservatism of the industry, the first international system was not put in place until 1986. The immense capacity of these systems have made possible the internet as we know it today.

In the late 1980s Trans-Pacific Cable 3, a joint venture by AT&T, Japan’s KDD, and several other companies, was one of the first optical cables to cross the Pacific. With TPC-3, “fiber-optic technology now links Europe, North America, and Asia,” proclaimed the New York Times in April 1989. This offered several advantages: it was a second or two faster than satellite transmissions, as well as more secure, cheaper to operate, and less prone to interference than copper lines.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Weltevreden, Batavia is today’s Sawah Besar, a section of Jakarta, Indonesia. The area was built up and named by the Dutch East India Company in the 17th and 18th centuries. In the 19th Century it became a full-fledged Dutch colony and in 1859 a telegraph cable was laid here connecting to Hong Kong. Had you arrived at that time, you would have found an established colonial city with a busy port. The area closer to the water held warehouses and offices of many trading companies. Weltevreden was more stately, with shops and government offices. Writings from that period describe the cable station as “one of the favourite stations in the Extension Co.” – it had a rambling garden, tennis courts, stables, a reading room, and a broad entryway flanked by palm trees. Today the area still bears traces of the earlier colonial period. The central square, laid out by the Dutch in the 19th century, displays symmetrical paths and gardens lined with palm trees, which lead to a statue celebrating Indonesia’s independence. In the same neighborhood, a large cathedral sits nearby a temple that is home to both Buddhist and Hindu practitioners, built in Dutch Colonial style.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: A trading post since the second century, the island of Singapore was a hub of exchange for Southeast Asia long before the British settled there in 1819. When the first underwater telegraph cable arrived forty years later, Singapore was a bustling port city, what one nineteenth-century cable survey called “that thriving halfway house between Europe and the East.” Although produced in a factory in London more than six thousand miles away, the Singapore-Muntok cable was insulated with the coagulated sap of trees native to the region. The Malays had used this substance, known as gutta-percha, for generations to make whips and other products. In the 1840s, a Scottish doctor stationed in Singapore took notice of the sap and brought it back to London. Gutta-percha made an ideal electrical insulator and became the material of choice in the cable industry.  By the time gutta-percha-encased wires populated Singapore's waters, demand had all but wiped out the local flora that made its transmissions possible.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Here you are received by Japanese hands. Annexed in 1910, Annam-ri remained under Japanese control until the end of World War II. The village is about 100 miles east from Japan’s westernmost island, and during the annexation, the Japanese government brought three cables ashore. The spot is ideal for a safe landing: a protected and quiet inlet with flat, grey waters and sandy beaches. Evergreen trees cover the gentle mountains sloping up past the beach. You don’t wonder where you are going next – there is but one option. Signals only shuttle back and forth from here to Japan.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: If you could climb up the deep green mountains on the northern end of this island, and look west across the water, you would see the hills of the Korean peninsula rising above Pusan. A small island, about 700 square kilometers of land, Tsushima is equidistant between the Japanese mainland and Korea. Because of its location, it had been a trade center for centuries before the cables arrived, and since has been a perfect locale for international cable connections as well as a strategic military node. Five different cables have landed here since 1891. In 1905, during the Russo-Japanese War, a decisive battle was fought in the waters around the island, which the Japanese won largely through their adeptness with wireless telegraphy. Yet this did not lead to the scrapping of “older” cable systems. Quite the opposite. After the war, the Japanese immediately laid a new undersea telegraph cable: wires complement, rather than replace, wireless.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Constructed in 2008 by a consortium of six telecom companies, the Trans-Pacific Express (TPE) cable is a major link between sites in the South China Sea (China, South Korea, and Taiwan) and the west coast of the United States. An extension to Japan opened in 2010. It greatly increased connection speeds across the Pacific, bringing them up to those found in trans-Atlantic cables.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Banyuwangi means "Fragrant Water" in Javanese. Landing on its shores in the late nineteenth century, you emerge from vibrant blue waves. A gateway between Asia and Australia, this Dutch colony is a key stopping point for telegraph cables. In 1871 a link to Darwin was landed here, connecting Australia to the rest of the world through Java’s shores. While more a century in the future, surfers will travel from around the world to ride Banyuwangi’s waves, nineteenth-century cablemen complain that its waters were “uninviting” because of the “ever-present danger of crocodiles and sharks.” Here the cable intersects both turbulent waters and an ancient spiritual history. From the sixteenth to eighteenth century, the city was the capital of the Hindi Kingdom of Blambangan, which controlled the eastern tip of Java before it was taken over by the Dutch. To dig a trench for the telegraph cable to Singapore, native convicts were employed as laborers. But when they unearthed a Hindu Temple from 700 AD, the laborers refused to continue and women, who reportedly were unaffected by the native “superstitions,” had to be called in to complete the job.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Kitaibaraki thrived as a center of coal mining in the nineteenth century, with rail lines connecting it to Tokyo a hundred miles away. In 2011, a 9.0-magnitude earthquake devastated the city. The closest cable station to the epicenter, Kitaibaraki was severed from both the U.S. and Asian networks, though Japan’s cable density allowed much of the traffic to be rerouted. The tsunami also wiped out an important cultural landmark: a red pagoda-like meditation retreat designed by Japanese philosopher and art historian Tenshin Okakura. While this structure was rebuilt in its original location on the rocky shores of the Pacific Ocean, cable operator KDDI announced the construction of a new tsunami-resistant station in Chikura that will stand ninety feet above sea level.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Built in the 1970s, Nanhui station was the first landing site for international coaxial cables in China. Early signals surfaced on the muddy shores of Nanhui district, then mostly farmland, roughly thirty miles southeast of central Shanghai. Now the area is almost unrecognizable, transformed by rapid industrialization that has displaced many of its former inhabitants. Large-scale development projects have even altered the local geography, continuing a process begun millennia ago when Nanhui was formed by silt deposited at the mouth of the Yangtze River. New cables pass by a huge artificial island that contains the recently constructed Shanghai deep-water container port, linked to the mainland by a twenty-mile bridge. And just east of the station, an entire city for 800,000 is being built from scratch on land reclaimed from Hangzhou Bay.

Busan is a major gateway for East Asian cable traffic, with five submarine networks interconnecting at this station. It is also where some of the best seaweed in South Korea is grown, one cableman tells you. Unfortunately, the boom in South Korean seaweed production, which comprises over half of the country’s aquaculture, doesn’t benefit international signal traffic. Dense seaweed forests immediately off Busan’s shore twist around ropes bordering the cable’s path. Harvesting them, fishermen come close to the country’s international communications lines. When building a new system, cable companies aren’t allowed to dig into the seabed, since this might disturb the fragile seaweed’s growth. Instead they carefully place each cable in a “mattress” before lowering it down into the crop.

Since the 1880s, Chikura has been known for precision exercises tied to the ocean. Every year, a knife ceremony is held at a local shrine dedicated to the gods of seasoning and culinary arts. Seven or eight men fillet and plate a whole carp using nothing but a twenty-inch blade and a pair of foot-long chopsticks, honoring the town’s legacy as a fishing community. In 1989, Chikura became a site of underwater cable innovation. The first fiber-optic line between the U.S. and Japan landed here, less than fifty miles from central Tokyo, followed by many other cables in the 1990s and 2000s. More recently, the town has become a surfing hub. Several professional competitions are held on Setohama Beach, where well-formed waves crash opposite the prominent cable station.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The Telekom Malysia (TM) cable landing station at Mersing is situated on an otherwise undeveloped beach roughly six miles south of the town center. Large signage on a curved, blue glass awning and a flag bearing the TM logo ensure that the site is highly visible from the coastal highway that passes nearby. Since the late 1990s, it has housed cables linking southeastern Malaysia to the rest of Asia, the U.S., the Middle East, and Western Europe. On their journey east, these cables intersect the offshore Seribuat Archipelago, for which Mersing’s ferry terminal is the main point of departure. As Malays, tourists, and communication signals are carried out to sea, north-south trade routes link Mersing to the rest of the Malay Peninsula as a site of tin, rubber, and palm oil production.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: A futuristic cable station sits next to the expansive wetlands of the Dongtan national wildlife sanctuary. Signals arrive through major underwater networks, while swans, cranes, spoonbills, shorebirds, and many species of fish stop here along their migratory routes. Like the landing station, Chongming Island’s salt-water marshes and tidal flats are transitional zones that mediate between land and sea. Although it feels rural, the island is only twenty miles from central Shanghai and is connected by a freeway. Visitors fill the tree-lined boardwalks that crisscross the reserve, observing the local fauna. Meanwhile, data is surveilled as it passes through the station: a white sign with red text marks the presence of underground cables and bears the name “PLA Unit 61398,” a group believed to engage in electronic monitoring and cyber-attacks against the U.S..

In 2012, a consortium of telecom companies led by China Unicom signed a construction and maintenance agreement for the Asia-Pacific Gateway (APG) cable system, due to open in 2015. The system is specially routed to avoid areas prone to seismic activity while providing additional capacity along the region’s existing international networks.
In 1891, the British Eastern Extension, Australasia & China Telegraph Company extended their networks to Medan.

In the early 1890s, a telegraph cable was brought to Medan, part of the rapid growth and industrialization the area had been experiencing over the past 50 years. In the 1820s it was a small village of 200 people, but with the development of tobacco plantations by Dutch colonists in the 1860s, the village quickly grew into a modern city. By 1910, it had population of 17,500. The cable arrived in the midst of this development: the port area bustled with trading ships and Chinese and Javanese laborers brought in to work in the tobacco industry.  The center of town was being built up to serve the Dutch businessmen: a post office, social club, city hall, and street cafes all were emerging, in colonial European architectural style. Grand stone buildings with pillars and arched windows and Germanic houses with red roofs lined the street where the cable station was built, just past a traditional Chinese archway that marked the entrance to the town.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Was located at 44 Northam Road, now Jalan Sultan Ahmad Shah.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In George Town at the turn of the 19th century you witness the beginnings of a modern city. The streets are lined with warehouses and ghauts, wide steps leading from the street to the water. Banks, trading areas, and emporium stores are beginning to appear along Beach Street. Since its founding by the British East India Company in 1786, the town has grown into a bustling trading port and commercial center. George Town has been built on water: its commercial center stands on a swampy wetland that was leveled and filled in the early 1800s. Seeing that this was precarious, English settlers built their bungalows high up on top of Penang Hill, forbidding natives to do the same. The settlers’ wealthy Chinese business partners were allowed to build in the middle part of the hill. The cable – part of the emerging modern city – surfaces close to the water, but ultimately connected those who lived far above it.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: By the 1990s, capacity was filling up at Hong Kong’s major cable station, and the cable companies looked for a place to expand. Lantau Island, a few miles away from Hong Kong, seemed ideal. It was to be the site for major infrastructure developments during that period: a new Hong Kong airport, a trans-bay expressway, and the AsiaWorld theme park were placed in what was otherwise a sprawling, sparsely populated jungle. The station builders chose Tong Fuk, a small village on the island’s southern shore, for their landing. When they went to construct the station, however, the village leaders resisted, worried that the cable stations would disrupt the feng shui of the land and bring them bad fortune. The stations were ultimately placed there, but were careful not to infringe upon the nearby shrine.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In 1900, the village of Naic in Cavite Province was joined to an offshore island by underwater telegraph cable as part of a U.S. Army Signal Corps operation to network the area around Manila. A century later, Naic became a landing site for EAC-C2C, bringing it into direct communication with the U.S. and several Asian countries. Owned by the Philippine Long Distance Telephone Company (PLDT), the station is located on the town’s outskirts near farmland, subdivisions, and a vast new horseracing complex with stables for 800 thoroughbreds. Even though they are broadcast online, spectators travel from as far as Manila to witness the races first-hand, a popular activity in the Philippines since the late nineteenth century. Some have even described the local telecommunications market, dominated by PLDT and Globe Telecom, as a two-horse race.

Past meets present in this northern district of New Taipei City, the vast municipality that surrounds Taiwan’s capital. Traditional Chinese sailing junks are constructed in a small shipyard adjacent to a huge, modern container port, built in the 1990s and early 2000s. Rice and peanuts are harvested by hand on the moist foothills of Guanyin Mountain while a local amusement park attracts visitors with one of the longest water slides in the region. At the same time that Pa Li (also known as Bali) is networked in space through shipping channels and a branch of the East Asia Crossing cable system, it is also connected across time. A museum of archeology showcases artifacts from Taiwan’s earliest inhabitants, unearthed during recent development. It includes a display called the “Bridge of Time,” which allows museumgoers to imaginatively visit a prehistoric Taiwanese culture that once thrived in the area.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The landing site at Ban Pak Bara in Satun province is Thailand’s only cable hub on the west coast and thus handles much of the country’s signal traffic to Europe and the Middle East. Some cables also continue from Satun overland to Songkhla, linking submarine networks in the Andaman Sea and Gulf of Thailand. Although a key international node, the station is overshadowed by its natural surroundings. From your landing place on the white sand beaches of this small fishing and agricultural community, you can see modest cinderblock communications buildings and towers across the road, surrounded by acres of mangrove trees. And looking back from where you came, your view is dominated by the lush and mountainous islands of Mu Ko Phetra National Park rising out of the water.

Although undersea fiber optic cables were introduced in the region in the 1980s, the TVH cable, completed in 1996, was the first system to link Thailand, Vietnam, and Hong Kong with a communications channel equivalent to 80,000 simultaneous phone calls.
Hawaii-5 was AT&T's second fiber-optic cable between California and Hawai'i, yet like their first fiber-optic link, the line was economically obsolete in only twelve years.

Central California has been a cable hub since 1964, when a telephone cable to Hawai'i was routed through Morro Bay. The first station in the area was constructed by AT&T, and its location midway between San Francisco and Los Angeles placed it out of the way of potential nuclear attack. 

Although the state has been a hub in communication technology, it has also played an important role in the growth of the environmental movement, pioneered breakthroughs in environmental policy, and is committed to the preservation of wilderness areas. Daniel Press articulates the apparent contradiction: “at the vanguard of paradoxical trends, California is one of the fastest growing states in the country, but is the most ambivalent about change.” Today there are increasing conflicts between these two forces.

In 1962, the balance of undersea cable power was shifting from British companies to the United States. The Keawa‘ula cable station had just been built on O‘ahu’s west shore to land the Commonwealth Pacific Cable. British transoceanic lines no longer stopped at Fanning Island, but rely on the United States. As such, its construction followed U.S. military specifications: it was located underground in a nuclear fallout shelter with walls that were feet thick. Arriving at this station today, you see an elegant set of steps up leading up to a front wall comprised of square glass blocks. One transmission engineer describes Keawa‘ula as a “palace.” Designed by a local Honolulu-based firm, the station's aboveground expansion was inspired by a visit from the CEO of Teleglobe Canada in the 1980s. With little space for gathering inside, the staff members at the time held their meeting in a small and cramped lunch room. Afterward, the CEO saw the station workers outside, joking around and hanging out in the trees like monkeys. In part inspired by the cable community, Teleglobe built a new, staff-friendly environment. The re-designed station grounded the communication hub in the heart of the cable family, yet left intact its Cold War foundations.

AT&T has been integral to the laying of submarine cables since the 1950s. During the Cold War period, cable laying was "club" affair - only nationally-affiliated telecommunications companies could participate. AT&T facilitated all of the United States' transoceanic projects during this time, and built an number of cable stations on US shores.

The Russian post and telegraph service laid this cable from Port Arthur to Tschifu. Only five years later, the cable was handed over to the Imperial Chinese Telegraph Company. Subsequently, Japan signed a treaty with China to operate the system.

Southwest of Dairen, at the tip of the Liaodong Peninsula, Port Arthur was an important Russian naval port at the turn of the twentieth century. It has a naturally protected southern harbor, allowing ships safe anchor throughout the year. In 1900, the Russians landed two telegraph cables here, one connecting south across the Yellow Sea to Tschifu, China and one connecting the longer distance west to Sasebo. This communications node would soon become Russia’s Achilles’ Heel: the cables were cut and intercepted by the Japanese leading up to and during the Russo-Japanese War.  Unable to receive reports or warnings, Port Arthur was then surprised when Japanese ships attacked. The Japanese took control of Port Arthur and from here were able to wage a successful war for the control of Manchurian land and sea. Unrest may have started even earlier, however: in the year before the war, cable ships record trips to repair breaks in the Port Arthur – Tschifu cable, due to “willful cutting.”
